Lab Architecture

Overview
This lab builds a network monitoring system that mirrors how enterprise infrastructure monitoring is designed with a dedicated monitoring zone, segmented networks, and zone-path awareness rather than just device-level monitoring.

The core design principle: monitor paths and zones, not just devices.

Physical layout

Everything runs as virtual machines on a single Windows host running VMware Workstation. The VMs are connected through VMware virtual networks (VMnets) that simulate real physical network segments.

Virtual machines

pfSense VM -> role: Firewall, gateway, and zone boundary enforcement

Network adapters:
Adapter 1: VMnet0 (Bridged) → WAN interface (em0) — gets IP from home router
Adapter 2: VMnet1 (Host-only) → LAN interface (em1) — 192.168.X.X
Adapter 3: VMnet2 (Host-only) → DMZ interface (em2) — 172.16.X.X

Why pfSense sits here: pfSense is the routing and security boundary between all three zones. Every packet crossing zones passes through pfSense and is evaluated against its firewall rules. 
This gives centralised traffic control and the ability to monitor inter-zone connectivity by checking whether pfSense can route between zones correctly.

